          {
            "type": "message",
            "id": "msg_4a21fb754fecbb37006a3ebc7e0ae08190b8e2e5ebea99ad39",
            "response_id": "resp_4a21fb754fecbb37006a3ebc7ae9fc819092b7fd0d4deaf20e",
            "role": "assistant",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "output_text",
                "text": "Microsoft Foundry Agent Service is Microsoft’s managed platform for building and running AI agents on top of Foundry models and “tools” (web search, file search, code interpreter, memory, MCP servers, etc.). It’s designed so you can create agents, give them capabilities, and expose them through stable endpoints without operating your own infrastructure. 【5:0†source】\n\n## What you can build with it (agent types)\n- **Prompt agents**: You author the agent’s instructions/config in the Foundry portal (or via SDK/REST), attach tools, pick a model, and Foundry runs it end-to-end—no app runtime/containers to manage. 【5:0†source】\n- **Hosted agents**: You bring your own agent code (using frameworks like Agent Framework, LangGraph, OpenAI Agents SDK, Anthropic Agent SDK, etc.), package it as a container, and Foundry runs it behind a managed endpoint with scaling, identity, and observability. (Hosted agents are described as *preview* in the doc.) 【5:0†source】\n\n## Key building blocks\n- **Responses API**: A “single entry point” to interact with agents and to give any runtime access to Foundry models + platform tools (like file search, code interpreter, memory, web search, MCP servers). 【5:0†source】\n- **Agent Runtime**: Manages conversation state, tool calls, hosting/scaling, and agent lifecycle. 【5:0†source】\n- **Tools**: Built-ins (web search, file search, memory, code interpreter, MCP) plus support for custom functions and managed auth patterns. 【5:0†source】\n- **Models**: Works across multiple models in the Foundry model catalog; you can swap models without rewriting the agent logic. 【5:0†source】\n- **Observability + security**: Tracing/metrics with Application Insights integration, and enterprise controls like Microsoft Entra identity/RBAC and other security features. 【5:0†source】\n\n## Tools: “knowledge” vs “action”\nIn the “classic” documentation Microsoft breaks tools into:\n- **Knowledge tools** (ground answers in data): e.g., web grounding, Azure AI Search, file search, Fabric, etc. 【5:1†source】\n- **Action tools** (do things): e.g., calling workflows via Logic Apps, using OpenAPI specs, MCP endpoints, function calling, browser automation, etc. 【5:1†source】\n\n## Classic vs the current service\nMicrosoft notes that **agents (classic) are deprecated and scheduled to retire on March 31, 2027**, and recommends using the newer “generally available” Foundry Agents/Agent Service instead, with newer tool catalog/docs. 【5:1†source】\n\n## What I need from you to tailor the explanation\n1) Are you using **Microsoft Foundry (new)** or **Foundry (classic)** today?  \n2) Do you want a **prompt-only agent** (no code) or a **code-based hosted agent**?  \n3) Where will it be used (internal app, Teams, Microsoft 365 Copilot, public API)? 【5:0†source】",
